03921nam a22006375i 9780813552033DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112012nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135520337 a10.36019/97808135520332doi  a(DE-B1597)529712  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aMED0000002bisacsh04a616.89/52221 aHermsen, Lisa M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aManic Minds :bMania's Mad History and Its Neuro-Future /cLisa M. Hermsen. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (172 p.) :b12 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF FIGURES -- tPREFACE AND ACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction: Mania’s mad history and its Neuro-future -- tChapter 1 Mania Multiplies with Fury textbook descriptions of the psychopathology -- tChapter 2 The Maniac and the Iconography of Reform -- tChapter 3 Midwestern Mania genetics in the heartland -- tChapter 4 Manic Lives mad memoirs -- tChapter 5 Neuropsychiatry, Pharmacology, and Imaging the New Mania -- tEpilogue -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX -- tABOUT THE AUTHOR0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom its first depictions in ancient medical literature to contemporary depictions in brain imaging, mania has been largely associated with its Greek roots, "to rage." Prior to the nineteenth century, "mania" was used interchangeably with "madness." Although its meanings shifted over time, the word remained layered with the type of madness first-century writers described: rage, fury, frenzy. Even now, the mental illness we know as bipolar disorder describes conditions of extreme irritability, inflated grandiosity, and excessive impulsivity. Spanning several centuries, Manic Minds traces the multiple ways in which the word "mania" has been used by popular, medical, and academic writers. It reveals why the rhetorical history of the word is key to appreciating descriptions and meanings of the "manic" episode." Lisa M. Hermsen examines the way medical professionals analyzed the manic condition during the nineteenth and twentieth centuries and offers the first in-depth analysis of contemporary manic autobiographies: bipolar figures who have written from within the illness itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aManic-depressive illnessxHistory. 0aNeuropsychiatryxHistory. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081355203340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813552033423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813552033.jpg  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK